# Objective: Know Your Audience {#objective:-know-your-audience}

**Why Change, Why Now**

Media & Advertising are in the midst of a painful transition as competition for human attention accelerates, business models collapse, and ad dollars rapidly move to the tech giants. This is due to consumer cord cutting, the shift to streaming, increased competition for human attention, increased competition of advertising / marketing budgets, and upheaval in the advertising markets.

The battle for human attention is what the media and advertising market actually competes on. Until the 2010’s, the population primarily consumed media composed of linear TV, print (magazines, newspapers and books), and audio/radio. By 2015, 65% of US adults were active users of and increasingly spending time on social media (Instagram and SnapChat). TikTok launched in the US in 2017 and experienced explosive growth in 2020 during the pandemic.

The media and advertising market has always been focused on capturing human attention and monetizing it through subscriptions, advertising and commerce. Over the past decade, a major shift has occurred where time spent watching TV has shifted to Social Media, Gaming and other digital media.

Consumer cord cutting is rapidly reducing distribution revenue for US based video media companies while shrinking the traditional TV audience for advertising globally. This results in revenue losses for distribution and advertising for media companies and advertising agencies. The US is a unique market in which Distributors/MVPDs (Multi Video Platform Distributors including Cable, Satellite, Telco and virtual services such as YouTube TV) pay media companies for the right to distribute their content to subscribers. As cord cutting accelerates, this revenue stream experiences decline. 

As the Pay TV ecosystem subscriber counts decline, the audience declines and thus advertising revenue declines. This affects both the sellers of ads (media companies), the buyers of ads (agencies) and tech, data and measurement companies that connect the buy with the sell side of the advertising ecosystem.

In June 2024, Streaming eclipsed traditional / Linear TV (Cable \+ Broadcast) for the first time with more than 50% of time spent on TV streaming \+ other non-linear viewership. This change is significant because it sets the stage for accelerated decline of the traditional pay TV package, while the new direct to consumer (DTC) streaming offerings are not replacing the traditional distribution revenue from pay TV forcing media companies to shrink to maintain profit margins. See Nielsen for more data: [https://www.nielsen.com/data-center/the-gauge/\#viewing-by-platform](https://www.nielsen.com/data-center/the-gauge/#viewing-by-platform)

With the rise of DTC Streaming apps, subscriber churn has become a major problem. Consumers have no qualms canceling a subscription when they finish watching the desired programming and resuming a subscription when new seasons are dropped. Churn was less of an issue with traditional Pay TV packages.

It also creates opportunities to provide enhanced, superior consumer experiences in the streaming offerings. DTC streaming apps typically have lower ad loads than traditional linear TV, but better ad targeting. The more targeted an ad is, the higher the price (or CPM) of that ad.

Traditional media is experiencing significantly increased advertising competition for advertising / marketing budgets over the past decade from:

* *Walled Gardens* (ad supported tech giants): Google, Meta and Amazon are projected to own more than 60% of the $450B advertising market in the US in 2025\. They are also expected to own more than 50% of the global $1.1 trillion in projected ad spend.  
* *Platforms* (Apple, Google Android, Amazon, Roku, Samsung, LG, etc): The traditional pay TV distributor (MVPD) is being partially replaced by the new digital platforms, operating systems, smart TVs, and app stores. Unfortunately for media companies, platforms do not pay for the right to distribute their apps. Instead they take rev share on advertising and DTC subscription revenue. All of the platforms leverage their relationship with and data on their customers to target and sell ads.   
* *Retail media networks* such as Amazon, Walmart Connect, Target Roundel, Instacart Ads, Kroger Precision Advertising, United Airlines Kinective Media, CVS Media Exchange and more are leveraging their commerce data to provide novel and powerful audience targeted advertising that is increasingly competing with the rest of the media ecosystem.

Beyond increased competition, the advertising market is in upheaval due to:

* *Audience Fragmentation*: as linear TV declined, it has become harder for marketers to reach the mass market.    
* *Signal loss*: cookie deprecation has decimated browser targeting and tracking outside of Chrome, Apple’s [App Tracking Transparency](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/apptrackingtransparency) framework has rendered most of the iOS ecosystem not targetable, Platform policies that strip digital identifiers (Device Advertising ID and IP Address) are negatively impacting ad targeting and measurement.  
* *Evolving privacy regulations*: the patchwork of rapidly evolving privacy regulations at a state level in the US and globally are causing all participants in the trillion dollar global advertising market to take more conservative stances around sharing data, targeting and reducing use of third party data where possible. This is challenging because third party data has been the dominant form of data used to target advertising.  
* *Measurement not keeping pace with consumer behavior*: The advertising ecosystem globally relies on measurement companies to provide third party counting of content and ads to provide a currency for buying and selling and planning. In the US, measurement has failed to keep pace with the shift to streaming and other mediums resulting in undercounting and over attribution of advertising results to Google search and other click based advertising mediums. This “last click attribution” approach has resulted in a shift in ad spend away from media companies that produce professional content to platforms that don’t actually create content but expose content through search, user generated content sites and social media.

*For any organization to compete in this environment*, they must adopt the playbook used by tech giants Google, Meta and Amazon including recognizing that Identity is the foundation of any Media and Advertising (M+A) business. Companies in this industry need to:

* Identify, track, and understand their audience across all of their experiences in a privacy-compliant manner  
* Learn their audience’s interests, intentions, demographics and psychographics  
* Support the future of audience activation for marketing, personalization, ad sales, insights, and analytics.  
* Leverage Machine Learning to predict everything from advertising outcomes, to churn, time spent consuming content and more.  
* Leverage GenAI to streamline workflows, improve margins, and automate processes that block new revenue streams.

The urgency to transform is driven by increasing competition for human attention, evolving business models, and the shift of ad dollars to digital giants Google, Meta and Amazon. M+A organizations must leverage Data \+ AI as Google, Meta, and Amazon do, or they risk failure in this rapidly changing landscape.

**Business Executives**

* Chief Revenue Officer (CRO)**:** Responsible for revenue across advertising sales, content distribution, licensing, and marketing.  
* Head of Ad Sales (President, Chairman, etc): Responsible for advertising sales revenue, strategy, products and execution.  
* EVP / SVP of Advanced or Digital Advertising: A leader in the ad sales organization specifically responsible for the strategy, products and possibly the sales there of around digital and addressable advertising experiences.  
* Chief Product Officer (CPO): Responsible for product strategy and management of audience experiences.  
* Chief Research, Analytics, Insights & Data Officer: Responsible for formulating data strategy and ensuring access to data to support the business.  
* Head of Data Strategy: The party ultimately responsible for defining and executing a data strategy that includes audience, identity and customer 360\.

## Strategic Priority: Identity & Customer 360 {#strategic-priority:-identity-&-customer-360}

### Why change, why now

Media companies reliant on advertising revenue are falling behind tech giants Google, Meta and Amazon as they capture more of the advertising market each year. Today those three tech giants have 60% of the US and 50% of the global advertising market. Media companies need to be more like the tech giants and embrace the usage of their First Party (1P) data for their advantage. Yet, today, Media companies run primarily off of Third Party (3P) data despite it being more expensive, more restrictive and less accurate than their 1P data due to ease of access and simple packaging.

Pure 1P Data without any 3P data affords organizations significantly more flexibility compared to 3P data sets.

1P Data Usage Solves for:

- Audience Fragmentation by providing the path to a unified view of the audience  
- Signal loss by avoiding 3P data tracking restrictions imposed by platforms  
- Evolving privacy regulations by minimizing risks associated with data licensing and sharing  
- Measurement by providing superior signal

Customer 360 (C360) offers a unified view of each customer’s interactions, preferences, and behaviors across all touchpoints. It unifies both 1P and 3P data (eg. Customer Profiles, Customer Engagement, Purchases, Clickstream), from multiple systems into one central place to enable personalized experiences, improve retention, and optimize campaigns to drive revenue growth. Note: The gold 1P data sets must not be comingled with 3P data, instead an abstraction layer should access the gold 1P data sets which can then co-mingle with 3P data.

However, Media companies struggle with common data challenges: 

* Disparate Data Silos: Multiple, often unintegrated systems for video streaming, ad delivery, subscriptions, and social engagement complicate unification.  
* Fragmented identities: Companies often times are managing 3-7 IDs per users  
* Unable to deliver Real-time engagement: Customers expect immediate, personalized recommendation, requiring constant updates and low-latency data processing  
* Unable to personalize at scale: Applying and deploying AI at scale is often limited in current customer data platform solutions.  
* Disconnected from data estate: Organizations are often duplicating data from traditional CDPs, creating friction between data and business (eg. Marketing, Advertising) teams to effectively deliver AI use cases with speed and at scale


Building a C360 hinges on accurately identifying individuals across apps, devices, and social media. An identity spine that reconciles all relevant identifiers—under strict privacy compliance—is critical for personalization and monetization.  However, fragmentation of 1P data, inconsistent 3P identifiers, and evolving privacy regulations pose ongoing challenges in creating/maintaining C360.  This is increasingly important today for Media organizations with privacy shifts and cookie deprecation, ever-increasing competition, rising customer expectations and choice, and monetization pressures. 

**Key Use Cases**

**Customer Event Ingestion**: the foundation for every other use case. Event data typically fall into two categories:

* **User Interactions**: Capture all user actions (e.g., content playback, navigation, scrolling), consumption patterns, and engagement to fuel user analytics and power personalized content recommendation systems, enabling insights into content popularity and user engagement metrics  
* **Client telemetry**: telemetry on the status and health of the application. For example, with a video streaming app, this could include data like the CDN used to serve the content, the bitrate, or any buffering events. These data feed into any frameworks for monitoring quality of service / experience for reporting and for operational use cases. This data is also used to assess how long a user consumes content, which is a passive signal.

**Identity Spine**: Develop a unified identity framework storing, organizing and transforming an enterprise's first-party, third-party, while supporting the ability to "combine" 1P and 3P data sources \- while always keeping them separate.

* **1P Identity Spine**: First party audience, PII data (Personally Identifiable Information) organized and stored at the household, person and possibly device level along with any internal or external IDs.  
* **3P Identity Spine**: Licensed third party data for enrichment (eg. demographics), stored at the household, person and device level (can include licensed 3P device graphs)  
* **Combined Spine**: Abstraction layer that prioritizes 1P data usage when available and enriched with 3P data as needed without intermingling source data sets. 

**House Hold Device Graphing**: Implement advanced techniques to link multiple devices to individual households or persons leveraging 1P signals. The resulting graph is then used to dramatically augment identity coverage across devices. 

**Customer Profiles**: Aggregation of data from multiple touchpoints and interactions across audience experiences to create an understanding of an audience member, customer, subscriber or household’s interests, preferences, demographics, psychographics and more.

**Audience Segmentation**: ML-driven algorithms create dynamic audience segments based on behavioral patterns, content preferences, and demographic information.

### Key Objectives/KPIs

* Increase identity resolution rate  
* Improve cross-device matching to households or profiles  
* Enhance customer profile completeness

**Business Value**

*Key ‘metrics’ to impact*

* *% Identity Coverage-* what % of all digital experiences are mapped to a customer ID in real time

*Why does % of Identity Coverage matter?*

* Advertisers want and will pay for (via higher CPMs)- validate users they can target in real-time  
  * Additionally, if ads are served to the wrong ‘sets of users’ the advertiser will demand ‘make goods’ (i.e. credits) equal to the wasted spend, reducing the media companies yield (i.e. profitability) on advertising inventory utilization.

*What are the economic impacts of improving Identity coverage (i.e. resolution)?*

* Direct increase to revenue & thus profits  
  * Being able to identify users in real time supporting audience targeting and advanced measurement / attribution can generate 25%-100% higher CPMs. Example below  
    * Before Databricks-   
      * CPM for ID’d users of $30 & CPM for non-ID’d of $20  
      * 10,000,000,000 impressions served per month with 30% ID’d  
      * Revenue= 30%\*10B\*$30/1,000 \+ 70%\*10B\*$20/1,000 \= $230M  
    * With Databricks-  
      * CPM for ID’d users of $30 & CPM for non-ID’d of $20  
      * 10,000,000,000 impressions served per month with 60% ID’d  
      * Revenue= 60%\*10B\*$30/1,000 \+ 40%\*1B\*$20/1,000 \= $260M  
      * **Increase revenue by $30M/month or $260M/year**.  
  * Reduction in ‘make goods’ from 40% to 20%. Example below  
    * Before Databricks-  
      * For a $10M ad campaign, validation IDs that 40% of budget went to ‘wrong users’   
      * Media seller will owe $4M back to brand/agency  
    * With Databricks-  
      * Due to improved ID Coverage, validation shows only 20% of spend went to ‘wrong users’  
      * Advertiser will have only $2M in ‘make good’ credits  
      * **Decrease in ad waste by 50% resulting in $2M additional profit for the campaign.**

### Client Event Ingestion on Databricks for Warner Bros. Discovery

This architecture showcases the robust data ingestion, processing, and analytics pipeline built on Databricks to support Warner Bros. Discovery's digital properties, including their flagship streaming platform, Max. The system is designed to handle the ingestion and processing of 16 billion watch events per day, ensuring scalability, security, and actionable insights across their ecosystem.

**Key Components**

Ingestion Layer

1. Streaming Ingestion:  
   * Client events from platforms like Max, CNN, Food Network, and others are ingested via Kafka.  
   * Tokenization of Personally Identifiable Information (PII) is performed using Amazon EKS and Amazon DynamoDB, ensuring data privacy and compliance.  
   * The processed data is passed to Databricks' Autoloader for efficient ingestion into Delta Lake.  
2. Batch Ingestion:  
   * Batch data ingestion is facilitated through Autoloader and native connectors, enabling seamless integration of first-party (1P) data such as subscriptions and user consent, as well as third-party (3P) data sources like Braze, Adobe, and LiveRamp.

Processing Layer

* Data is processed using powerful tools like Apache Spark and dbt, transforming raw event data into business-ready datasets.  
* The pipeline follows the Delta Lake architecture:  
  * Bronze Tables: Raw data storage.  
  * Silver Tables: Cleaned and enriched data.  
  * Gold Tables: Refined datasets optimized for analytics and machine learning.

Unity Catalog & Semantic Layer

* The Unity Catalog serves as a unified governance framework to manage metadata, access control, and lineage across datasets.  
* A Semantic Layer acts as a collection of views over key tables, delivering business-ready datasets that fuel downstream analytics and machine learning workflows.

Downstream Applications

1. Machine Learning (ML):  
   * Leveraging tools like MLflow, TensorFlow, OpenAI, and Flyte to build predictive models for growth and retention analysis, content discovery algorithms, and quality-of-experience optimization.  
2. Analytics / Serving:  
   * Advanced business intelligence powered by Looker, Tableau, and AI/BI solutions enables Warner Bros. Discovery to derive actionable insights for financial integration, AdTech strategies, customer behavior analysis, and more.  
   * Databricks SQL and integration with platforms like Snowflake (via Uniform) ensures fast querying for various use cases.  
   * 

**Business Impact**

This architecture forms the backbone of Warner Bros. Discovery’s data-driven decision-making processes. By seamlessly ingesting client events from diverse digital properties into a unified platform powered by Databricks and Unity Catalog:

* Warner Bros. Discovery ensures high-quality user experiences across Max and other platforms.

# Objective: Grow and Retain Your Audience {#objective:-grow-and-retain-your-audience}

## Strategic Priority: Marketing {#strategic-priority:-marketing}

**Context: Why Change, Why Now**

Media companies must embrace change now because they are engaged in a fierce war for attention against one another, competing to capture increasingly fragmented and distracted audiences. With an overwhelming volume of content vying for limited audience focus, traditional marketing methods are no longer enough. Media companies must adopt more sophisticated, data-driven marketing strategies that cut through the noise by delivering highly personalized and engaging experiences. This means shifting toward integrated, real-time campaigns that build fan loyalty through social media engagement, influencer collaborations, and user-generated content. The urgency to change is clear: in this battle for attention, companies that adapt quickly will dominate, while those slow to evolve risk losing their share of audience engagement and relevance in an increasingly competitive market.

**Top Data & AI Use Cases**

1. Customer Data Platform (CDP): Centralizing and unifying customer data from various touchpoints into a single platform, enabling more personalized and effective marketing strategies.  
2. Customer Identity Resolution: Merging and matching customer data from different sources to create a unified, accurate profile, enhancing targeting and customer insights.  
3. Lifecycle Marketing: personalized marketing throughout the subscriber lifecycle, optimizing touchpoints for acquisition, retention, re-engagement, and cross-sell/up-sell.  
4. Predictive Churn Analysis: Analyzing customer behavior patterns to predict churn and inform targeted interventions aimed at improving retention rates.  
5. Measurement & Attribution: Generate robust measurement and attribution models for advertising campaigns leveraging 1P, 2P and 3P data.  
6. Media Mix Modeling: Evaluating the performance of marketing channels to optimize budget allocation and improve the overall impact of campaigns across multiple touchpoints.

**Databricks Technical Advantage**

* Real-time analytics: process large volumes of clickstream data in real time to enhance the customer experience.   
* Data collaboration: seamlessly connect to the marketing ecosystem for identity resolution, data enrichment, activation, and journey orchestration.   
* Databricks SQL & AIBI: democratize data access to unlock insights and accelerate innovation.  
* Advanced ML/AI: enhance customer profiles using predictive analytics (e.g. propensity to churn, lifetime value)  
* GenAI: streamline processes and hyper-personalize customer experiences using AI Agents

For example, an alias like "Champion" can be assigned to the model version currently in production, making it easier to reference and update the production model.**Environment Management**: Unity Catalog uses a three-level namespace (catalog.schema.model\_name) to organize models, reflecting their environment (e.g., dev, qa, prod) and associated governance rules. This structure helps in managing models across different stages of their lifecycle.**Model Sharing**: Models can be shared across workspaces within the same region, and with appropriate privileges, users can access models from any workspace attached to the metastore containing the model. This enables seamless collaboration and model comparison.**CRUD Operations**: Unity Catalog supports CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations on registered models through the MLflow REST/client APIs. This ensures that models can be managed programmatically and integrated into CI/CD workflows These features will allow Data Analysts, Data Scientists and business users to easily collaborate on new data and AI use cases. |

# Appendix: Vertical Overview {#appendix:-vertical-overview}

As Communications and Gaming have moved into their own verticals, it is important to redefine the sub-verticals of Media & Entertainment (M\&E). M\&E is composed of the following sub and sub-sub verticals:

* Media and Advertising (M+A)  
* Sports  
* Entertainment

**Media and Advertising**  
The Media and Advertising industries are intrinsically intertwined with Advertising typically generating half to the majority of revenue of these organizations. This sub vertical functions as an interconnected ecosystem with specialized enterprises providing essential services, while competitors even collaborate to innovate and reduce friction across the market.

- **Media**  
  Organizations that create, distribute, or monetize content and human attention through selling advertising and subscriptions.  
  - **Video Media: Video Streaming, Television, Film, Distribution**  
    - Streaming and Television covers traditional broadcasting as well as digital and streaming services, which have become increasingly popular with the advent of streaming platforms like Netflix and Disney+. Additional examples include: Hulu, YouTube TV, Fubo, Max, and Paramount+.  
    - Film encompasses the production, distribution, and exhibition of movies, including both traditional cinema and digital releases. Example companies include Warner Bros. Studios, Paramount Studios, Universal Studios.  
    - While Telco MVPDs, OEMs, and major tech platforms are not part of M\&A, they distribute most of the video content globally. Thus, they are a critical component of the ecosystem that must be accounted for. Examples include: Charter Communications, Comcast, DirecTV.  
  - **Audio Media: Music, Radio, Audio Streaming, Podcasting**  
    - Music involves the creation, production, and distribution of music across various platforms, including streaming services like Spotify and Apple Music.  
    - Includes traditional AM/FM broadcasting as well as digital radio and podcasts, which have seen significant growth in recent years. Examples include Audacy, iHeart Radio, Cumulus, and SiriusXM.   
  - **Digital Media and Publishing: Social media, Platforms, Apps, Sites, Print**  
    - Digital Media encompasses online content, social media, and other digital platforms that distribute information and advertising. Examples include Meta, TikTok, Snap, Yahoo, Pinterest.  
    - Publishing covers books, newspapers, business information, and magazines, both in print and digital formats. Examples include Conde Nast, DotDash Meredith.  
  - **Out of Home (OOH): Billboards**  
    - OOH organizations manage and sell billboards, transit ads, and digital out of home ads. Examples include Outfront Media, JCDecaux, Clear Channel.  
- **Tech, Data and Measurement: Connecting ad sellers & buyers**  
  Organizations that provide the technology and data that powers the content and advertising ecosystems.  
  - **Tech: Ad Tech, Mar Tech, Content Tech**  
    - Ad Tech and Mar Tech:  
      - Demand Side Platforms (DSPs): The Trade Desk  
      - Supply Side Platforms (SSPs): Magnite, Comcast FreeWheel  
      - Ad Servers: Comcast FreeWheel, Magnite Spring Serve, Innovid  
      - Customer Data Platforms (CDPs): Amperity, Hightouch, Adobe Real Time CDP  
      - Customer Relationship Management (CRM): Salesforce  
      - Content Management Systems (CMSs) and Online Video Platforms (OVPs): WordPress, QuickPlay, Brightcove  
      - Email Marketing Platforms: Constant Contact  
      - Social Media Management Tools: Sprout Social  
      - Marketing and Content Automation Platforms: HubSpot  
      - Content Delivery Networks (CDNs): Akamai  
  - **Data: Service Providers, Third Party Data Providers**  
    - Data companies that are not part of agencies or media. These organizations collect, cleanse, organize and resell data to support the ecosystem. They also provide data services such as audience onboarding and matching.  
    - Examples include: Vizio, SambaTV, TransUnion, Experian, LiveRamp, AdStra, Deepsync, MRI Simmons.  
  - **Measurement and Attribution**  
    - Specialized, neutral players that measure content, ads, and audience as well as calculating effectiveness of advertising (attribution).  
    - Examples include Integral Ad Science, DoubleVerify, Nielsen, VideoAmp, iSpot.  
- **Agencies & Resellers: ad planning, creative, buying**  
  Organizations that support marketers / brands to promote their products or services through various forms of media.  
  - **Advertising Agencies**  
    - Organizations that represent marketers to plan, buy, optimize and measure advertising. Inclusive of full service, digital, media buying, social media, and branding agencies. Agency Hold Co’s may also include data companies. Examples include Publicis Groupe, IPG, Omnicom, WPP/GroupM, Horizon, Dentsu, Havas.  
  - **Creative Agencies**  
    - Concentrate on the design and creation of advertising materials, such as logos, graphics, and print ads. They excel in developing the visual aspects of a brand's marketing efforts. Examples include divisions of the aforementioned advertising agencies.  
  - **Public Relations Agencies**  
    - Manage a company's public image and relationships with the media. They handle press releases, media relations, and crisis management to enhance a brand's reputation. Examples include: Edelman, Weber Shandwick, Ketchum, FleishmanHillard, and BCW.  
  - **Resellers & Networks**  
    - Resellers are typically networks that combine technology, data and measurement to resell ad inventory from media cos in a way that adds value to the buyer. Examples include Simulmedia, Cadent, Active International.

**Sports: Leagues, Teams & Venues**

The professional sports industry is a vast and dynamic sector that encompasses various sports, teams, leagues, and related activities.

Examples include leagues like the National Football League (NFL), National Basketball Association (NBA), Major League Baseball (MLB), Premier League (Soccer/Futbol), Formula 1, as well as the individual teams and organizations that comprise the leagues \- e.g., Texas Rangers, Indiana Pacers, Manchester City Futbol Club, and more.

**Entertainment: Ticketing, Events & Venues**

Entertainment encompasses a broad spectrum of events, including concerts, theater performances, and festivals, creating immersive experiences for audiences worldwide. Customer examples include LiveNation, StubHub, Madison Square Garden.

Google, Meta and Amazon have captured more than their fair share of ad revenue \- 60% of US ($450B) and 50% of global ($1.1T), yet they mostly don’t create content and Globally advertising is forecasted to grow more than 7% YoY.

Media companies are sitting on vast amounts of First Party (1P) data that are more accurate and valuable than Third Party (3P) data yet wildly under utilized. Tech Giants embrace the usage of 1P data for their advantage. Not only is it less expensive to use one’s own 1P data, it affords significant flexibility when it comes to privacy policy and regulation restrictions imposed by governments (federal and state) and platforms (Apple, Google, Amazon, Roku, etc). With 1P data organizations can solve the problems created by the advertising market being in upheaval due to Signal loss and Evolving privacy regulations.

Scalable Infrastructure

* Delta Lake: Open-format storage ensures cost-effective scalability while maintaining flexibility for downstream analytics and machine learning.  
* Auto-scaling & Performance Optimization: Databricks auto-scales resources to handle large volumes of streaming or batch data without manual intervention.

* Higher CPMs Through Real-Time Targeting: Improved identity resolution increases CPMs by up to 50–100%, directly boosting ad revenue.  
* Reduction in Ad Waste: Enhanced targeting reduces "make-good credits" due to misaligned ad placements, improving profitability.  
* Predictive Analytics: Machine learning models predict key metrics like churn, lifetime value, and ad performance to optimize marketing strategies.

Generative AI for Innovation

* Ad Creative Personalization: Automates the generation of localized or platform-specific ad creatives using generative AI tools like Mosaic AI.  
* Content Discovery & Recommendations: Supports retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) pipelines for personalized user experiences in streaming apps or digital media platforms.
